1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:04,740
Now, once we've covered the basics of NLP and transformer architecture,

2

00:00:04,740  -->  00:00:09,320
let's briefly cover what are we going to do for the rest of the lesson.

3

00:00:09,320  -->  00:00:14,880
In this lesson, we will be working on implementing a transformer model from scratch.

4

00:00:14,880  -->  00:00:17,920
Instead of generating a text on any topic,

5

00:00:17,920  -->  00:00:24,160
we'll limit our goals and create a model that can generate Shakespeare like poetry.

6

00:00:24,160  -->  00:00:28,880
We will train it on the work of William Shakespeare an English poet,

7

00:00:28,880  -->  00:00:33,890
and it should be able to start generating poetry that looks like his work.

8

00:00:33,890  -->  00:00:37,880
Our model will have an architecture that is similar to

9

00:00:37,880  -->  00:00:42,180
the one used in GPT models created by Open AI,

10

00:00:42,180  -->  00:00:46,140
and we'll see how these models work step by step.

11

00:00:46,140  -->  00:00:51,920
There will be a few major differences between our model and GPT models.

12

00:00:51,920  -->  00:00:54,930
First of all, our model will be much smaller.

13

00:00:54,930  -->  00:00:58,820
It will have a few order of magnitude less parameters,

14

00:00:58,820  -->  00:01:02,380
but this also means that we will be able to train it

15

00:01:02,380  -->  00:01:06,480
without spending a fortune on computers and electricity.

16

00:01:06,480  -->  00:01:10,380
We will use a character level tokenizer instead of using

17

00:01:10,380  -->  00:01:15,060
a sub-word tokenizer to keep our implementation simpler.

18

00:01:15,060  -->  00:01:18,960
Finally, the model implementation will be focused

19

00:01:18,960  -->  00:01:23,225
on understandability rather than performance.

20

00:01:23,225  -->  00:01:28,590
Once we're done, we will be able to create an instance of our model,

21

00:01:28,590  -->  00:01:32,810
provide a configuration that will include several parameters,

22

00:01:32,810  -->  00:01:36,090
like context window size, and so on.

23

00:01:36,090  -->  00:01:42,050
Then we will be able to generate text using our model and a provided prompt.

24

00:01:42,050  -->  00:01:45,670
L suggested to write a phrase that Romeo,

25

00:01:45,670  -->  00:01:50,890
which is one of the characters in the Shakespeare work, could have side.
